   =20
      Twitter vote
   =20
 =20

Twitter Inc.=E2=80=99s shareholders are voting today on whether to sell the=
 company=C2=A0to Elon Musk at $54.20 per share. Twitter closed yesterday at=
 $41.41 per share. There is not much suspense here. If you have stock that =
is worth $41.41 per share, and someone wants to buy it from you at $54.20, =
you should let him. Twitter is easily going to get its votes.
  [1]
=C2=A0The  Wall Street Journal reports:
Early votes show investors approving the deal by a wide margin, the people =
said, though there is always a chance that the results could change as shar=
eholders can alter their votes through a meeting scheduled for Tuesday at 1=
 p.m. Eastern time.
I do not actually think there=E2=80=99s much chance that the results could =
change. If you are a Twitter shareholder, what could possibly happen betwee=
n now and 1 p.m. that would make you=C2=A0not=C2=A0want to cash out at $54.=
20?
There are a few complications. One is that news is definitely happening abo=
ut Twitter today. Peiter =E2=80=9CMudge=E2=80=9D Zatko, Twitter=E2=80=99s f=
ormer head of security who has turned whistle-blower, testified in Congress=
=C2=A0today about how bad Twitter=E2=80=99s security=C2=A0is. But nothing t=
hat he says is going to make Twitter shareholders=C2=A0less=C2=A0likely to =
vote for the deal. The worse Twitter is, the more excited you should be abo=
ut getting $54.20 for your Twitter shares. If Zatko showed up at this heari=
ng and said =E2=80=9Cactually Twitter=E2=80=99s security is great and they=
=E2=80=99ve discovered cold fusion=E2=80=9D then I guess you should vote to=
 keep your shares; in a world where Twitter is worth much more than $54.20 =
on its own, the vote will probably fail. But he didn=E2=80=99t say that.
Another complication is that, of course, voting to sell to Musk at $54.20 d=
oesn=E2=80=99t mean it=E2=80=99ll actually happen. Musk has terminated the =
deal (three times!) because he claims that Twitter has breached some condit=
ions and so he doesn=E2=80=99t have to actually buy it; a Delaware court wi=
ll decide if he=E2=80=99s right about any of those things. I tend to think =
that he=E2=80=99s wrong and will have to close, but I don=E2=80=99t have es=
pecially huge confidence in that belief, and the market-implied odds aren=
=E2=80=99t that great, which is why the stock is trading at $41.41. Still, =
if you are a Twitter shareholder, you have to vote yes on the deal, because=
 if everyone votes no then the deal is=C2=A0definitely=C2=A0dead; if shareh=
olders don=E2=80=99t approve the deal, that gives Musk a fourth and unassai=
lable reason for terminating it.
  [2]
=C2=A0The shareholders voting to close the deal is a necessary but not suff=
icient condition to the deal closing. Which is why they=E2=80=99ll vote yes=
.
A third complication is that Twitter=E2=80=99s  biggest shareholder is, uh,=
 Elon Musk,
  [3]
=C2=A0and he=E2=80=99s trying to get out of the deal. Could he vote his 9.5=
% stake in Twitter against=C2=A0the deal, thus preventing it from closing? =
Well. The merger agreement (section 6.2(d)) says that he has to vote in fav=
or of the deal, but he claims to have terminated the agreement (three times=
!) so perhaps he no longer feels bound by that, and it is a bit awkward for=
 him to vote yes on a deal that he wants to get out of. What will he do? Eh=
, it doesn=E2=80=99t really matter; I=E2=80=99m pretty sure that Twitter is=
 going to get a huge majority and won=E2=80=99t actually need Musk=E2=80=99=
s votes.

