 =20
   =20
      Twitter whistle-blower
   =20
 =20

Surely the   highest-variance aspect of the Twitter vs. Musk saga is Zatko=
=E2=80=99s whistle-blower complaint. If Zatko can make a compelling case th=
at Twitter is horribly bad =E2=80=94=C2=A0that its information security is =
so bad that it violates the law, that it has fraudulently concealed its pro=
blems, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that is probably Musk=E2=80=99s best argume=
nt to get out of the deal: Twitter is doing fraud, it has suffered a materi=
al adverse effect, etc. If Zatko is just a run-of-the-mill paranoid securit=
y researcher who is aggrieved about being fired and making mountains out of=
 molehills, then his complaint will quickly be kicked out of court and won=
=E2=80=99t affect the Musk deal. Zatko=E2=80=99s credibility =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0whether he=E2=80=99s telling the truth, and also whether he is exaggerat=
ing or underselling the importance=C2=A0of Twitter=E2=80=99s problems =E2=
=80=94 is a key input into your evaluation of Twitter=E2=80=99s stock value=
. The more credible he is, the less likely it is that Twitter will get $54.=
20 per share,=C2=A0and the less Twitter will be worth without Musk=E2=80=99=
s deal.
So if you are a hedge fund, or an expert-network firm working on behalf of =
hedge funds, you obviously want to know how credible he is. You might, for =
instance, want to talk to some of his old coworkers to get a feel for him. =
You might offer to pay them a lot of money for a one-hour phone call, becau=
se you might have a lot of money riding on the Twitter deal, which means sp=
ecifically that you have a lot of money riding on your evaluation of Zatko=
=E2=80=99s credibility.
At the New Yorker, Ronan Farrow has a story on =E2=80=9CThe Search for Dirt=
 on the Twitter Whistle-Blower=E2=80=9D:
The dozens of e-mails and LinkedIn messages received by people in Zatko=E2=
=80=99s professional orbit appeared to be mostly from research-and-advisory=
 companies, part of a burgeoning industry whose clients include investment =
firms and individuals jockeying for financial advantage through information=
. At least six research outfits=E2=80=94Gerson Lehrman Group (G.L.G.), Alph=
aSights, Mosaic Research Management, Ridgetop Research, Coleman Research Gr=
oup, and Guidepoint=E2=80=94approached former colleagues of Zatko=E2=80=99s=
 at Stripe, Google, and the Pentagon research agency=C2=A0DARPA. All offere=
d to pay for information, sometimes noting that the compensation would be h=
igh or apparently unrestricted. At least two investment firms, Farallon Cap=
ital Management L.L.C. and Pentwater Capital Management L.P., also sought i=
nformation from individuals close to Zatko.
I have to say that Farrow, and Zatko=E2=80=99s former coworkers, seem a lot=
 more shocked by this than I am. Yes, right now, for a series of weird reas=
ons, information about whether Peiter=C2=A0Zatko is or is not a good guy is=
 incredibly valuable to hedge funds, and they will pay =E2=80=9Chigh or app=
arently unrestricted=E2=80=9D amounts of money for some informal chats with=
 his former colleagues about their impressions of the guy. Sometimes that i=
s how financial markets work. You get paid for incorporating information in=
to prices.=C2=A0
That said I particularly enjoyed this reaction:
Two members of Musk=E2=80=99s team, who asked not to be named, owing to the=
 sensitivity of the ongoing litigation, said that they also had no connecti=
on to the inquiries. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a lot of hedge funds currentl=
y betting that the deal flows. And so they=E2=80=99re doing everything they=
 possibly can to undermine that not happening,=E2=80=9D one of them told me=
. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s obviously wrong. You can=E2=80=99t discredit a witn=
ess, as opposed to listening to what he has to say and taking seriously the=
se security threats. . . . That should be the priority, not making a buck.=
=E2=80=9D
Yeah no of course, right, Elon Musk=E2=80=99s priority in evaluating Zatko=
=E2=80=99s complaint is solely about =E2=80=9Ctaking seriously these securi=
ty threats=E2=80=9D; he has no economic interest at all in Zatko=E2=80=99s =
credibility and is just dispassionately following the truth wherever it lea=
ds.

