<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Surely the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/29038310.263540/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vc=
GluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjkvbXVzay10cmllcy1hLW5ldy13YXktb3V0LW9mLXR3=
aXR0ZXI_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDkxMzIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwOTEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa194a1bd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  highest-variance aspect</a> of =
the Twitter vs. Musk saga is Zatko=E2=80=99s whistle-blower complaint. If Z=
atko can make a compelling case that Twitter is horribly bad =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0that its information security is so bad that it violates the law, that i=
t has fraudulently concealed its problems, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0then that is=
 probably Musk=E2=80=99s best argument to get out of the deal: Twitter is d=
oing fraud, it has suffered a material adverse effect, etc. If Zatko is jus=
t a run-of-the-mill paranoid security researcher who is aggrieved about bei=
ng fired and making mountains out of molehills, then his complaint will qui=
ckly be kicked out of court and won=E2=80=99t affect the Musk deal. Zatko=
=E2=80=99s credibility =E2=80=94=C2=A0whether he=E2=80=99s telling the trut=
h, and also whether he is exaggerating or underselling the <em>importance=
=C2=A0</em>of Twitter=E2=80=99s problems =E2=80=94 is a key input into your=
 evaluation of Twitter=E2=80=99s stock value. The more credible he is, the =
less likely it is that Twitter will get $54.20 per share,=C2=A0and the less=
 Twitter will be worth without Musk=E2=80=99s deal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So if you are a hedge fund, or an expert-netwo=
rk firm working on behalf of hedge funds, you obviously want to know how cr=
edible he is. You might, for instance, want to talk to some of his old cowo=
rkers to get a feel for him. You might offer to pay them a lot of money for=
 a one-hour phone call, because you might have a lot of money riding on the=
 Twitter deal, which means specifically that you have a lot of money riding=
 on your evaluation of Zatko=E2=80=99s credibility.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the New Yorker, Ronan Farrow has a story on=
 =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29038310=
.263540/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubmV3eW9ya2VyLmNvbS9uZXdzL25ld3MtZGVzay90aGUtc2VhcmN=
oLWZvci1kaXJ0LW9uLXRoZS10d2l0dGVyLXdoaXN0bGUtYmxvd2Vy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB0e501f6c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">The Search for Dirt on the Twitter Whistle-Blower</a>=
=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The dozens of e-mails and LinkedIn=
 messages received by people in Zatko=E2=80=99s professional orbit appeared=
 to be mostly from research-and-advisory companies, part of a burgeoning in=
dustry whose clients include investment firms and individuals jockeying for=
 financial advantage through information. At least six research outfits=E2=
=80=94Gerson Lehrman Group (G.L.G.), AlphaSights, Mosaic Research Managemen=
t, Ridgetop Research, Coleman Research Group, and Guidepoint=E2=80=94approa=
ched former colleagues of Zatko=E2=80=99s at Stripe, Google, and the Pentag=
on research agency=C2=A0DARPA. All offered to pay for information, sometime=
s noting that the compensation would be high or apparently unrestricted. At=
 least two investment firms, Farallon Capital Management L.L.C. and Pentwat=
er Capital Management L.P., also sought information from individuals close =
to Zatko.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have to say that Farrow, and Zatko=E2=80=99s=
 former coworkers, seem a lot more shocked by this than I am. Yes, right no=
w, for a series of weird reasons, information about whether Peiter=C2=A0Zat=
ko is or is not a good guy is incredibly valuable to hedge funds, and they =
will pay =E2=80=9Chigh or apparently unrestricted=E2=80=9D amounts of money=
 for some informal chats with his former colleagues about their impressions=
 of the guy. Sometimes that is how financial markets work. You get paid for=
 incorporating information into prices.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said I particularly enjoyed this reaction=
:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Two members of Musk=E2=80=99s team=
, who asked not to be named, owing to the sensitivity of the ongoing litiga=
tion, said that they also had no connection to the inquiries. =E2=80=9CTher=
e=E2=80=99s a lot of hedge funds currently betting that the deal flows. And=
 so they=E2=80=99re doing everything they possibly can to undermine that no=
t happening,=E2=80=9D one of them told me. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s obviously =
wrong. You can=E2=80=99t discredit a witness, as opposed to listening to wh=
at he has to say and taking seriously these security threats. . . . That sh=
ould be the priority, not making a buck.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah no of course, right, Elon Musk=E2=80=99s =
priority in evaluating Zatko=E2=80=99s complaint is solely about =E2=80=9Ct=
aking seriously these security threats=E2=80=9D; he has no economic interes=
t at all in Zatko=E2=80=99s credibility and is just dispassionately followi=
ng the truth wherever it leads.</p>
